{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a231827a93ee2648", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tPERCEIVED ANNOYANCE IN MULTI-SOURCE ELECTRIC\n2\tVEHICLE AVAS ENVIRONMENTS\n3\tBerkay KULLUKCU\n4\tChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\n5\temail: berkay.kullukcu@tu-dresden.de\n6\t\n7\tJonas KRAUTWURM\n8\tChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\n9\temail: jonas_lukas.krautwurm@tu-dresden.de\n10\t\n11\tSerkan ATAMER\n12\tChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\n13\temail: serkan.atamer@tu-dresden.de\n14\t\n15\tErcan ALTINSOY\n16\tChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\n17\tCentre for Tactile Internet with Human-in-the-Loop (CeTI), TU Dresden, Dresden, 01069, Saxony,\n18\tGermany\n19\tResearch Cluster 6G-life, TU Dresden, Dresden, 01069, Saxony, Germany\n20\temail: ercan.altinsoy@tu-dresden.de\n21\tThe increasing usage of electric vehicles in urban environments has resulted in a widespread presence\n22\tof AVAS sounds. While individual vehicle sound design and testing is a common approach, real-world\n23\ttraffic scenarios often involve the simultaneous presence of multiple vehicles. Their combined presence\n24\tmay lead to changes in perception, compared to when they are presented individually, specifically\n25\tregarding annoyance. The work addresses annoyance perception in scenarios involving multiple electric\n26\tvehicle AVAS sounds. It changes the traditional isolated source-based view into a scene-based one by\n27\tinvestigating the combined presence of multiple vehicle sounds as they are experienced in realistic\n28\ttraffic environments. Binaural listening tests were conducted using recorded electric vehicle pass-by\n29\tsounds. The stimuli presented different traffic scenarios, including single and multiple-vehicles.\n30\tSelected stimuli were spatially arranged to simulate vehicles approaching from opposite directions.\n31\tAfter each stimulus, participants rated their perceived annoyance, enabling a comparison of annoyance\n32\tresponses between isolated and multiple AVAS sound scenarios. The test investigated how different\n33\tlevels of overlapping AVAS sounds affect perceived annoyance when multiple electric vehicles are\n34\tpassing by.\n35\t\n36\tKeywords: acoustic vehicle alerting system (AVAS), electric vehicle, annoyance, auditory scene,\n37\tbinaural listening test\n38\t\n39\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n40\t\n41\t1. Introduction\n42\tThe electrification of road transport is changing the soundscapes of our cities. At low speeds, the\n43\tpropulsion noise of electric and hybrid vehicles is often substantially reduced in comparison to\n44\tconventional internal combustion engine vehicles, which is beneficial to the sound quality and public\n45\thealth in our cities. However, the reduced audibility has also been linked to safety concerns regarding\n46\tvisually impaired pedestrians who often rely on their ability to hear the approaching vehicle to understand\n47\tthe vehicle's presence, distance, and direction of approach [1-6].\n48\tMost of the evaluation strategies for AVAS detection, identification, and sound quality follow a\n49\tsource-centric approach. Early studies focused on quantifying the increase in crash risk for hybrid\n50\tvehicles during low-speed manoeuvres and confirmed the detection of quiet vehicles at shorter distances\n51\tthan conventional vehicles [3, 4]. Other studies focused on quantifying reaction times or detection\n52\tdistances using binaural recording and controlled soundscapes, demonstrating strong dependencies on\n53\tbackground noise, signal spectra, and temporal/spectral modulation effects [5, 6, 12–17]. These studies\n54\tare all highly relevant but follow an implicit assumption that the target vehicle is auditorily separable\n55\tand can be attributed to a single source.\n56\tFrom the environmental noise point of view, the interaction of two or more noise sources has been\n57\twell understood and studied over the years. However, in the case of the long-term response of the\n58\tcommunity to environmental noise, it is not possible to predict the combined annoyance response through\n59\tthe simple addition of the energy from the two noise sources. This is why the annoyance equivalent\n60\tmodel transforms the noise from the two sources into the equivalent exposure to a reference source and\n61\tthen adds them up [18]. Environmental noise standards acknowledge the co-occurrence of two or more\n62\tnoise sources and recommend the systematic description and reporting of the annoyance results [11, 19].\n63\tHowever, these are usually related to long-term exposure (hours to years), whereas the AVAS perception\n64\tin the case of road traffic usually involves short bursts (seconds), often with strong contextual cues such\n65\tas the ability to see the source, motion, and the spatial location of the source.\n66\tAs regards the short-term assessment of the sound quality and annoyance of AVAS signals,\n67\tpsychoacoustic models may be considered as providing valuable additional descriptors. These may\n68\tinclude the Zwicker loudness model (ISO 532), and related descriptors such as sharpness (DIN 45692),\n69\tas well as tonality, roughness, and fluctuation strength, which may help to relate the sound features to\n70\tthe listener’s perception [20-23]. Annoyance models using psychoacoustics combine several descriptors\n71\tto predict annoyance levels more accurately than single descriptors such as sound pressure levels, in\n72\tparticular tonal and modulated sounds [24]. However, it is not clear whether these models, which are\n73\tnormally derived from single sounds, can account for the interaction effects observed when several\n74\tAVAS signals are present in the scene.\n75\tThe soundscape in the city is not determined only by the sound pressure levels but is also related to\n76\tthe perception of the scene in which the sounds are embedded. This leads to the assessment of the scene\n77\tas perceived in the context, rather than assessing the individual sources [9]. This change in assessment\n78\tis particularly relevant to the assessment of AVAS signals because the sound from one vehicle may be\n79\tacceptable in isolation but become problematic in the context of several sources: several tonal sources\n80\tmay beat together, make tones more prominent, and increase the perception of crowding in the scene.\n81\tMoreover, AVAS is not the sole contributor to low-speed exterior noise. Instead, tire-road and\n82\tauxiliary sounds dominate the scene with increasing speed. The relative contribution of AVAS depends\n83\ton the vehicle and ambient environments [9, 25, 26]. Therefore, the scene-based method should treat\n84\tAVAS as part of the traffic soundscape.\n85\tStudies on combined source annoyance have demonstrated that annoyance is not necessarily related\n86\tto the A-weighted sound levels of the sources in question. The annoyance equivalent calculation is the\n87\t\n88\t2│8\n89\t\n90\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n91\t\n92\tsum of the annoyance equivalent levels of the sources in question [18]. Several reviews and conference\n93\treports have demonstrated that the exposure-annoyance relationship varies from source to source, which\n94\tmeans that the results of the annoyance equivalent calculation may not be accurate [27].\n95\tThis study examines the effect of overlapping AVAS sources on the annoyance of people when sounds\n96\tare played in a controlled environment. The general idea behind this work is that a scene with multiple\n97\tAVAS sources isn’t the sum of the individual AVAS sources, as the overlapping of these sources can\n98\tactually increase the annoyance of the scene, or in some cases, reduce it by the interaction of the tones.\n99\t\n100\t2. Method\n101\tA synthesized sound from [28] (S1) was used in the listening tests together with binaural pass-by\n102\trecordings of electric vehicles with AVAS as the source material (Ford Kuga (S2) and Ford E-Transit\n103\t(S3)). The spectrograms of the sounds are given in Figure 1 a, b, c respectively. The vehicle movement\n104\twas modelled as a constant velocity pass-by at 20 km/h directly in front of the listener (Figure 2). For\n105\tthe two-vehicle scenes, the spatial arrangement of the vehicles was varied on a two-lane road with\n106\topposing directions, and the time offset was varied to create simultaneous crossing, +1 s, and +2 s of\n107\tdelay between the two vehicles (one vehicle passes 1 or 2 s before the other vehicle, directly in front of\n108\tthe listener). The auralization was conducted using a virtual acoustics renderer (TASCAR) [29] with a\n109\tground reflector and HRTF-based receiver model. Tire rolling noise was added to the TASCAR\n110\tenvironment and played together with each AVAS sound, taken from a real-world recording of a Cupra\n111\tBorn driving at a stable 20 km/h (Figure 3).\n112\t\n113\ta) Sound 1\n114\t\n115\tb) Sound 2\n116\t\n117\tc) Sound 3\n118\tFigure 1: FFT vs time spectrograms of the sounds used in the experiment.\n119\t\n120\tA total of N = 10 participants (5 males, 5 females, mean age: 30.7, std. dev.: 6.5 years) were presented\n121\twith the stimuli through headphones in a quiet room and rated perceived annoyance on a continuous 0–\n122\t3│8\n123\t\n124\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n125\t\n126\t100 scale for 13 stimuli (three single-vehicle pass-bys and ten two-vehicle scenes). Each stimulus was\n127\tpresented twice; ratings were averaged per participant and stimulus before group analysis. Head LabO2\n128\twas used as the sound reproduction device. All the AVAS sound files were maximum SPL equalized\n129\tbefore they were used in the experiments.\n130\t\n131\tFigure 2: A 2D schematic of the simulation environment generated in TASCAR.\n132\t\n133\tFigure 3: A microphone was placed directly towards to the rear-right wheel to decrease the interference of the\n134\tvehicle`s own AVAS in the simulations\n135\t\n136\t3. Results\n137\tFigure 4 summarizes raw annoyance ratings (mean across subjects ±95% CI) and their A-weighted\n138\tsound pressure levels (𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 ), averaged for the 2 seconds where the cars were passing directly in front of\n139\tthe listener, for all stimuli. The list of names on the y-axis represents each stimulus, where the first sound\n140\tname appears in multi-AVAS conditions is the AVAS of the vehicle coming from left to right (for\n141\texample in S1-S3, S1 is the AVAS of the vehicle coming from left to right.)\n142\t\n143\t4│8\n144\t\n145\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n146\t\n147\tSingle-vehicle ratings were similar across sounds (means: 46.4 points when averaged across S1–S3;\n148\tindividual means: S1 (47.1±11.7), S2 (45.2±8.7), S3 (46.9±10.9)). Two-vehicle scenes showed higher\n149\taverage annoyance (means: simultaneous 52.9, time-offset 52.7). The highest mean annoyance occurred\n150\tfor S1+S3 (58.0±7.6), S1+S2 with 1 s offset (57.0±9.0), S1 with 2 s offset relative to S2 (56.7±9.1)\n151\t(values in points ±95% CI). The mean within-subject increase was 6.54 points (95% CI [2.46, 10.63]).\n152\tA paired t-test indicated a significant difference (t(9)=3.14, p=0.012), which was confirmed by a\n153\tWilcoxon signed-rank test (p=0.014). After Holm correction across three planned contrasts, the\n154\tsimultaneous-vs-single comparison remained significant (p=0.036). In addition to this, the overall\n155\tpsychoacoustic Impulsiveness (Hearing Model) showed a strong association with the mean annoyance\n156\t(Spearman ρ = 0.823, p = 0.0006, BH–FDR q = 0.047).\n157\tDelayed (time-offset) two-vehicle scenes showed a similar mean increase (6.31 points), but with\n158\tlarger between-subject variability (95% CI [-1.32, 13.94]) and no significant difference from singlevehicle stimuli (p=0.139). When all two-vehicle scenes were pooled, the mean increase was 6.45 points\n159\t(p=0.043), but this pooled test did not remain significant after Holm correction.\n160\t\n161\tFigure 4: Results of the experiment, showing mean scores for all of the test conditions with the corresponding\n162\terror bars. 𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 ranges 71.73–74.13 dB, SD 0.77 dB (mean 72.91 dB).\n163\t\n164\tWe also tested whether swapping the approach direction/lane assignment changes annoyance by\n165\tpaired within-subject comparisons of stimuli with identical sound content but reversed order (S1+S2 vs\n166\tS2+S1, S1+S3 vs S3+S1, S2+S3 vs S3+S2), also having the effect that the near-lane vehicle (first sound\n167\tin the label) being acoustically louder at pass-by. No swap comparison was significant (S1/S2:\n168\tp(t)=0.226, p(W)=0.264; S1/S3: p(t)=0.236, p(W)=0.264; S2/S3: p(t)=0.833, p(W)=0.846), and the\n169\tcombined direction index (participant-wise mean across the three swaps) was −0.75 points with 95% CI\n170\t[−5.70, +4.20] (p(t)=0.773, p(W)=0.557). Additionally, 𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 did not explain annoyance (Spearman ρ=0.154, p=0.616).\n171\t\n172\t4. Discussion\n173\tThe results verify the underlying theory of short-term scene annoyance in multiple-source AVAS\n174\tscenes being not possible to predict from single-vehicle results. Scenes with two vehicles with annoyance\n175\t5│8\n176\t\n177\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n178\t\n179\tlevels greater than the baseline, calculated as the average of their constituent single-vehicle AVAS, are\n180\tdepicted in Figure 4. The results are in line with the overall body of work on noise annoyance from\n181\tmultiple sources, where it is known that annoyance is non-additive and dependent on source interaction\n182\trather than simple summation of all noise sources. Although it is a short-term rather than a long-term\n183\tstudy, with a corresponding short-term scene annoyance rather than a long-term community exposure, it\n184\tis interesting to note that a similar effect is seen. The effect is dependent on the composition of the scene.\n185\tA possible explanation for this is the theory of auditory scene organization and information masking.\n186\tFor a scene with two moving vehicles, auditory organization is necessary. Recent work has highlighted\n187\tthat multiple electric vehicles can affect auditory localization and perceptual judgments in ways that are\n188\tnot captured by single-source testing [18]. Confusion can lead to a number of problems with annoyance,\n189\tas it is possible that a greater annoyance is felt as a result of a confused brain attributing the sounds. This\n190\tis in line with the theory of soundscape, where it is suggested that soundscape perception is of primary\n191\timportance for evaluating a scene, rather than the sounds within it.\n192\tLastly, the differences observed highlight the possible interest in integrating perceptual tests and\n193\tpsychoacoustic parameters and annoyance modelling [20-24]. A key psychoacoustic result is that overall\n194\tImpulsiveness (Hearing Model) was the strongest correlate of mean annoyance.\n195\t\n196\t5. Conclusion\n197\tThis study aimed to explore the level of annoyance in short duration multi-source AVAS scenes using\n198\ta binaural auralization technique with single- and two-vehicle pass-by sounds. In N=10 participants,\n199\tsimultaneous two-vehicle scenes were rated significantly more annoying than single-vehicle stimuli on\n200\tthe raw 0–100 scale. The result supports a scene-based view of AVAS evaluation, in which the multisource context can change annoyance responses compared with isolated presentations. Furthermore, the\n201\tincreased annoyance in multi-source scenes could not be explained by residual level differences.\n202\tLimitations include the small number of participants, the limited set of stimuli, and the fixed speed.\n203\tFuture work is needed to increase the number of the stimulus set, including more AVAS scenes, types of\n204\tvehicles, and types of background sounds. It is also important to extend the scene manipulation space to\n205\tinclude more than two vehicles, varying the lane distance, and including realistic intersection scenarios.\n206\tFinally, it is important to explore the use of psychoacoustic and scene-based metrics as predictors of\n207\tmulti-source AVAS annoyance, in order to allow the use of optimization models in relation to the design\n208\tof AVAS scenes in realistic traffic scenarios.\n209\t\n210\tAcknowledgments\n211\tThis work was supported by the Joint project 6G-life, under Grant 16KISK001K and as a part of\n212\tGermany’s Excellence Strategy – EXC 2050/1 – Project ID 390696704 – Cluster of Excellence “Centre\n213\tfor Tactile Internet with Human-in-the-Loop” (CeTI) of TU Dresden. This work was supported by the\n214\tDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG, German Research Foundation) -444809588 as a part of the\n215\tpriority program AUDICTIVE - SPP2236. This conference participation was supported by the German\n216\tAcademic Exchange Service (DAAD) under the Kongressreisenprogramm.\n217\t\n218\tREFERENCES\n219\t1. World Health Organization. Environmental noise guidelines for the European Region, WHO\n220\t\n221\tRegional Office for Europe (2019).\n222\t\n223\t6│8\n224\t\n225\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n226\t\n227\t2. R. Guski, D. Schreckenberg and R. Schuemer, “WHO Environmental Noise Guidelines for\n228\t\n229\tthe European Region: A systematic review on environmental noise and annoyance,”\n230\tInternational Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, 14(12), 1539 (2017).\n231\t3. R. Hanna, Incidence of Pedestrian and Bicyclist Crashes by Hybrid Electric Passenger\n232\t\n233\tVehicles (DOT HS 811 204), National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, Washington,\n234\tDC (2009).\n235\t4. J. Wu, R. Austin and C.-L. Chen, Incidence Rates of Pedestrian and Bicyclist Crashes by\n236\t\n237\tHybrid Electric Passenger Vehicles: An Update (DOT HS 811 526), National Highway\n238\tTraffic Safety Administration, Washington, DC (2011).\n239\t5. L. Garay-Vega, A. Hastings, J. K. Pollard, M. Zuschlag and M. D. Stearns, Quieter Cars and\n240\t\n241\tthe Safety of Blind Pedestrians: Phase I (DOT HS 811 304), National Highway Traffic Safety\n242\tAdministration / Volpe Center, Washington, DC (2010).\n243\t6. D. S. Kim, R. Wall Emerson, K. Naghshineh, J. Pliskow and K. Myers, “Impact of adding\n244\t\n245\tartificially generated alert sound to hybrid electric vehicles on their detectability by\n246\tpedestrians who are blind,” Journal of Rehabilitation Research and Development, 49(3),\n247\t381–393 (2012). DOI: 10.1682/jrrd.2011.03.0041.\n248\t7. E. Altinsoy, “The detectability of conventional, hybrid and electric vehicle sounds by\n249\t\n250\tsighted, visually impaired and blind pedestrians,” in Proceedings of INTER-NOISE 2013,\n251\tInnsbruck, Austria (2013).\n252\t8. J. Grosse, R. Weber and S. Van de Par, “Comparison of detection threshold measurements\n253\t\n254\tand modeling for approaching electric cars and conventional cars presented in traffic and\n255\tpink noise,” Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics, 19, 050192 (2013). DOI:\n256\t10.1121/1.4806658.\n257\t9. E. Parizet, W. Ellermeier and R. Robart, “Auditory warnings for electric vehicles:\n258\t\n259\tDetectability in normal-vision and visually-impaired listeners,” Applied Acoustics, 86, 50–\n260\t58 (2014). DOI: 10.1016/j.apacoust.2014.05.006.\n261\t10. P. Poveda-Martínez, R. Peral-Orts, N. Campillo-Davo, J. Nescolarde-Selva, M. Lloret-\n262\t\n263\tCliment and J. Ramis-Soriano, “Study of the effectiveness of electric vehicle warning sounds\n264\tdepending on the urban environment,” Applied Acoustics (2017). DOI:\n265\t10.1016/j.apacoust.2016.10.003.\n266\t11. M.-C. Hsieh, H.-J. Chen, M.-L. Tong and C.-W. Yan, “Effect of environmental noise,\n267\t\n268\tdistance and warning sound on pedestrians’ auditory detectability of electric vehicles,”\n269\tInternational Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, 18(17), 9290 (2021).\n270\t12. M. J. Roan, L. Neurauter, M. Song and M. Miller, “Probability of detection of electric\n271\t\n272\tvehicles with and without added warning sounds,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of\n273\tAmerica, 149(1), 599 (2021). DOI: 10.1121/10.0003386.\n274\t13. L. Müller, J. Forssén and W. Kropp, “Auditory localization of multiple stationary electric\n275\t\n276\tvehicles,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, 157(3), 2029–2041 (2025).\n277\tDOI: 10.1121/10.0036248.\n278\t14. H. M. E. Miedema, “Relationship between exposure to multiple noise sources and noise\n279\t\n280\tannoyance,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, 116(2), 949–957 (2004).\n281\tDOI: 10.1121/1.1766305.\n282\t7│8\n283\t\n284\t\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n285\t\n286\t15. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO/TS 15666:2021, Acoustics—\n287\t\n288\tAssessment of noise annoyance by means of social and socio-acoustic surveys, ISO (2021).\n289\t16. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 532-1:2017, Acoustics—Methods\n290\t\n291\tfor calculating loudness—Part 1: Zwicker method, ISO (2017).\n292\t17. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 532-2:2017, Acoustics—Methods\n293\t\n294\tfor calculating loudness—Part 2: Moore-Glasberg method, ISO (2017).\n295\t18. Ecma International. ECMA-418-2: Psychoacoustic metrics for ITT equipment —Part 2\n296\t\n297\t(methods for describing human perception based on the Sottek Hearing Model), 4th edition,\n298\tEcma International (2025).\n299\t19. G. Q. Di, “Improvement of Zwicker’s psychoacoustic annoyance model aiming at tonal\n300\t\n301\tnoises,” Applied Acoustics (2016).\n302\t20. H. Campello-Vicente, R. Peral-Orts, N. Campillo-Davo and E. Velasco-Sanchez, “The effect\n303\t\n304\tof electric vehicles on urban noise maps,” Applied Acoustics, 116, 59–64 (2017). DOI:\n305\t10.1016/j.apacoust.2016.09.018.\n306\t21. L. Müller and W. Kropp, “Auralization of electric vehicles for the perceptual evaluation of\n307\t\n308\tacoustic vehicle alerting\n309\t10.1051/aacus/2024025.\n310\t\n311\tsystems,”\n312\t\n313\tActa\n314\t\n315\tAcustica,\n316\t\n317\t8,\n318\t\n319\t27\n320\t\n321\t(2024).\n322\t\n323\tDOI:\n324\t\n325\t22. S. Eggers, “Combination of Noise from Different Sources—an Overview,” in Proceedings\n326\t\n327\tof INTER-NOISE 2019 (2019).\n328\t23. T. Walton, A. J. Torija and A. S. Elliott, “Development of electric scooter alerting sounds\n329\t\n330\tusing psychoacoustical metrics,” Applied Acoustics, 201, 109136 (2022). DOI:\n331\t10.1016/j.apacoust.2022.109136.\n332\t24. T. Walton, A. J. Torija, R. J. Hughes and A. S. Elliott, “Evaluation of auditory alerting\n333\tsystems for safe electric scooter operations,” Scientific Reports, 15, 3424 (2025). DOI:\n334\t10.1038/s41598-024-80975-1.\n335\t25. SAE International. SAE J2889/1_201511: Measurement of Minimum Noise Emitted by\n336\tRoad Vehicles, SAE International (2015).\n337\t26. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 16254:2024, Acoustics —\n338\t\n339\tMeasurement of sound emitted by road vehicles of category M and N at standstill and low\n340\tspeed operation — Engineering method, ISO (2024).\n341\t27. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 12913-1:2014; ISO/TS 12913-\n342\t\n343\t2:2018; ISO/TS 12913-3:2019, Acoustics—Soundscape series, ISO (2014–2019).\n344\t28. L. Steinbach, S. Atamer and E. Altinsoy, „Evaluation of electric vehicle sounds, new\n345\tconcepts regarding speed-dependency and prediction of the warning effect,” 173rd Meeting\n346\tof Acoustical Society of America and 8th Forum Acusticum, (2017). DOI:\n347\t10.1121/2.0000567.\n348\t29. Y. G. Grimm, J. Luberadzka and V. Hohmann, „A Toolbox for Rendering Virtual Acoustic\n349\tEnvironments in the Context of Audiology,” Acta Acustica United with Acustica, Vol. 105\n350\t566 – 578, (2019). DOI: 10.3813/AAA.919337.\n351\t.\n352\t\n353\t8│8\n354\t\n355\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "c83b99e4-536d-4026-9c14-18643172c029", "uuid": "1ae9345b-2769-43a7-924b-50ff7405e55f", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T18:04:53.182Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_text.txt", "content": "PERCEIVED ANNOYANCE IN MULTI-SOURCE ELECTRIC\nVEHICLE AVAS ENVIRONMENTS\nBerkay KULLUKCU\nChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\nemail: berkay.kullukcu@tu-dresden.de\n\nJonas KRAUTWURM\nChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\nemail: jonas_lukas.krautwurm@tu-dresden.de\n\nSerkan ATAMER\nChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\nemail: serkan.atamer@tu-dresden.de\n\nErcan ALTINSOY\nChair of Acoustics and Haptics, TU Dresden, 01062 Dresden, Germany\nCentre for Tactile Internet with Human-in-the-Loop (CeTI), TU Dresden, Dresden, 01069, Saxony,\nGermany\nResearch Cluster 6G-life, TU Dresden, Dresden, 01069, Saxony, Germany\nemail: ercan.altinsoy@tu-dresden.de\nThe increasing usage of electric vehicles in urban environments has resulted in a widespread presence\nof AVAS sounds. While individual vehicle sound design and testing is a common approach, real-world\ntraffic scenarios often involve the simultaneous presence of multiple vehicles. Their combined presence\nmay lead to changes in perception, compared to when they are presented individually, specifically\nregarding annoyance. The work addresses annoyance perception in scenarios involving multiple electric\nvehicle AVAS sounds. It changes the traditional isolated source-based view into a scene-based one by\ninvestigating the combined presence of multiple vehicle sounds as they are experienced in realistic\ntraffic environments. Binaural listening tests were conducted using recorded electric vehicle pass-by\nsounds. The stimuli presented different traffic scenarios, including single and multiple-vehicles.\nSelected stimuli were spatially arranged to simulate vehicles approaching from opposite directions.\nAfter each stimulus, participants rated their perceived annoyance, enabling a comparison of annoyance\nresponses between isolated and multiple AVAS sound scenarios. The test investigated how different\nlevels of overlapping AVAS sounds affect perceived annoyance when multiple electric vehicles are\npassing by.\n\nKeywords: acoustic vehicle alerting system (AVAS), electric vehicle, annoyance, auditory scene,\nbinaural listening test\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\n1. Introduction\nThe electrification of road transport is changing the soundscapes of our cities. At low speeds, the\npropulsion noise of electric and hybrid vehicles is often substantially reduced in comparison to\nconventional internal combustion engine vehicles, which is beneficial to the sound quality and public\nhealth in our cities. However, the reduced audibility has also been linked to safety concerns regarding\nvisually impaired pedestrians who often rely on their ability to hear the approaching vehicle to understand\nthe vehicle's presence, distance, and direction of approach [1-6].\nMost of the evaluation strategies for AVAS detection, identification, and sound quality follow a\nsource-centric approach. Early studies focused on quantifying the increase in crash risk for hybrid\nvehicles during low-speed manoeuvres and confirmed the detection of quiet vehicles at shorter distances\nthan conventional vehicles [3, 4]. Other studies focused on quantifying reaction times or detection\ndistances using binaural recording and controlled soundscapes, demonstrating strong dependencies on\nbackground noise, signal spectra, and temporal/spectral modulation effects [5, 6, 12–17]. These studies\nare all highly relevant but follow an implicit assumption that the target vehicle is auditorily separable\nand can be attributed to a single source.\nFrom the environmental noise point of view, the interaction of two or more noise sources has been\nwell understood and studied over the years. However, in the case of the long-term response of the\ncommunity to environmental noise, it is not possible to predict the combined annoyance response through\nthe simple addition of the energy from the two noise sources. This is why the annoyance equivalent\nmodel transforms the noise from the two sources into the equivalent exposure to a reference source and\nthen adds them up [18]. Environmental noise standards acknowledge the co-occurrence of two or more\nnoise sources and recommend the systematic description and reporting of the annoyance results [11, 19].\nHowever, these are usually related to long-term exposure (hours to years), whereas the AVAS perception\nin the case of road traffic usually involves short bursts (seconds), often with strong contextual cues such\nas the ability to see the source, motion, and the spatial location of the source.\nAs regards the short-term assessment of the sound quality and annoyance of AVAS signals,\npsychoacoustic models may be considered as providing valuable additional descriptors. These may\ninclude the Zwicker loudness model (ISO 532), and related descriptors such as sharpness (DIN 45692),\nas well as tonality, roughness, and fluctuation strength, which may help to relate the sound features to\nthe listener’s perception [20-23]. Annoyance models using psychoacoustics combine several descriptors\nto predict annoyance levels more accurately than single descriptors such as sound pressure levels, in\nparticular tonal and modulated sounds [24]. However, it is not clear whether these models, which are\nnormally derived from single sounds, can account for the interaction effects observed when several\nAVAS signals are present in the scene.\nThe soundscape in the city is not determined only by the sound pressure levels but is also related to\nthe perception of the scene in which the sounds are embedded. This leads to the assessment of the scene\nas perceived in the context, rather than assessing the individual sources [9]. This change in assessment\nis particularly relevant to the assessment of AVAS signals because the sound from one vehicle may be\nacceptable in isolation but become problematic in the context of several sources: several tonal sources\nmay beat together, make tones more prominent, and increase the perception of crowding in the scene.\nMoreover, AVAS is not the sole contributor to low-speed exterior noise. Instead, tire-road and\nauxiliary sounds dominate the scene with increasing speed. The relative contribution of AVAS depends\non the vehicle and ambient environments [9, 25, 26]. Therefore, the scene-based method should treat\nAVAS as part of the traffic soundscape.\nStudies on combined source annoyance have demonstrated that annoyance is not necessarily related\nto the A-weighted sound levels of the sources in question. The annoyance equivalent calculation is the\n\n2│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\nsum of the annoyance equivalent levels of the sources in question [18]. Several reviews and conference\nreports have demonstrated that the exposure-annoyance relationship varies from source to source, which\nmeans that the results of the annoyance equivalent calculation may not be accurate [27].\nThis study examines the effect of overlapping AVAS sources on the annoyance of people when sounds\nare played in a controlled environment. The general idea behind this work is that a scene with multiple\nAVAS sources isn’t the sum of the individual AVAS sources, as the overlapping of these sources can\nactually increase the annoyance of the scene, or in some cases, reduce it by the interaction of the tones.\n\n2. Method\nA synthesized sound from [28] (S1) was used in the listening tests together with binaural pass-by\nrecordings of electric vehicles with AVAS as the source material (Ford Kuga (S2) and Ford E-Transit\n(S3)). The spectrograms of the sounds are given in Figure 1 a, b, c respectively. The vehicle movement\nwas modelled as a constant velocity pass-by at 20 km/h directly in front of the listener (Figure 2). For\nthe two-vehicle scenes, the spatial arrangement of the vehicles was varied on a two-lane road with\nopposing directions, and the time offset was varied to create simultaneous crossing, +1 s, and +2 s of\ndelay between the two vehicles (one vehicle passes 1 or 2 s before the other vehicle, directly in front of\nthe listener). The auralization was conducted using a virtual acoustics renderer (TASCAR) [29] with a\nground reflector and HRTF-based receiver model. Tire rolling noise was added to the TASCAR\nenvironment and played together with each AVAS sound, taken from a real-world recording of a Cupra\nBorn driving at a stable 20 km/h (Figure 3).\n\na) Sound 1\n\nb) Sound 2\n\nc) Sound 3\nFigure 1: FFT vs time spectrograms of the sounds used in the experiment.\n\nA total of N = 10 participants (5 males, 5 females, mean age: 30.7, std. dev.: 6.5 years) were presented\nwith the stimuli through headphones in a quiet room and rated perceived annoyance on a continuous 0–\n3│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\n100 scale for 13 stimuli (three single-vehicle pass-bys and ten two-vehicle scenes). Each stimulus was\npresented twice; ratings were averaged per participant and stimulus before group analysis. Head LabO2\nwas used as the sound reproduction device. All the AVAS sound files were maximum SPL equalized\nbefore they were used in the experiments.\n\nFigure 2: A 2D schematic of the simulation environment generated in TASCAR.\n\nFigure 3: A microphone was placed directly towards to the rear-right wheel to decrease the interference of the\nvehicle`s own AVAS in the simulations\n\n3. Results\nFigure 4 summarizes raw annoyance ratings (mean across subjects ±95% CI) and their A-weighted\nsound pressure levels (𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 ), averaged for the 2 seconds where the cars were passing directly in front of\nthe listener, for all stimuli. The list of names on the y-axis represents each stimulus, where the first sound\nname appears in multi-AVAS conditions is the AVAS of the vehicle coming from left to right (for\nexample in S1-S3, S1 is the AVAS of the vehicle coming from left to right.)\n\n4│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\nSingle-vehicle ratings were similar across sounds (means: 46.4 points when averaged across S1–S3;\nindividual means: S1 (47.1±11.7), S2 (45.2±8.7), S3 (46.9±10.9)). Two-vehicle scenes showed higher\naverage annoyance (means: simultaneous 52.9, time-offset 52.7). The highest mean annoyance occurred\nfor S1+S3 (58.0±7.6), S1+S2 with 1 s offset (57.0±9.0), S1 with 2 s offset relative to S2 (56.7±9.1)\n(values in points ±95% CI). The mean within-subject increase was 6.54 points (95% CI [2.46, 10.63]).\nA paired t-test indicated a significant difference (t(9)=3.14, p=0.012), which was confirmed by a\nWilcoxon signed-rank test (p=0.014). After Holm correction across three planned contrasts, the\nsimultaneous-vs-single comparison remained significant (p=0.036). In addition to this, the overall\npsychoacoustic Impulsiveness (Hearing Model) showed a strong association with the mean annoyance\n(Spearman ρ = 0.823, p = 0.0006, BH–FDR q = 0.047).\nDelayed (time-offset) two-vehicle scenes showed a similar mean increase (6.31 points), but with\nlarger between-subject variability (95% CI [-1.32, 13.94]) and no significant difference from singlevehicle stimuli (p=0.139). When all two-vehicle scenes were pooled, the mean increase was 6.45 points\n(p=0.043), but this pooled test did not remain significant after Holm correction.\n\nFigure 4: Results of the experiment, showing mean scores for all of the test conditions with the corresponding\nerror bars. 𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 ranges 71.73–74.13 dB, SD 0.77 dB (mean 72.91 dB).\n\nWe also tested whether swapping the approach direction/lane assignment changes annoyance by\npaired within-subject comparisons of stimuli with identical sound content but reversed order (S1+S2 vs\nS2+S1, S1+S3 vs S3+S1, S2+S3 vs S3+S2), also having the effect that the near-lane vehicle (first sound\nin the label) being acoustically louder at pass-by. No swap comparison was significant (S1/S2:\np(t)=0.226, p(W)=0.264; S1/S3: p(t)=0.236, p(W)=0.264; S2/S3: p(t)=0.833, p(W)=0.846), and the\ncombined direction index (participant-wise mean across the three swaps) was −0.75 points with 95% CI\n[−5.70, +4.20] (p(t)=0.773, p(W)=0.557). Additionally, 𝐿𝐴𝑒𝑞 did not explain annoyance (Spearman ρ=0.154, p=0.616).\n\n4. Discussion\nThe results verify the underlying theory of short-term scene annoyance in multiple-source AVAS\nscenes being not possible to predict from single-vehicle results. Scenes with two vehicles with annoyance\n5│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\nlevels greater than the baseline, calculated as the average of their constituent single-vehicle AVAS, are\ndepicted in Figure 4. The results are in line with the overall body of work on noise annoyance from\nmultiple sources, where it is known that annoyance is non-additive and dependent on source interaction\nrather than simple summation of all noise sources. Although it is a short-term rather than a long-term\nstudy, with a corresponding short-term scene annoyance rather than a long-term community exposure, it\nis interesting to note that a similar effect is seen. The effect is dependent on the composition of the scene.\nA possible explanation for this is the theory of auditory scene organization and information masking.\nFor a scene with two moving vehicles, auditory organization is necessary. Recent work has highlighted\nthat multiple electric vehicles can affect auditory localization and perceptual judgments in ways that are\nnot captured by single-source testing [18]. Confusion can lead to a number of problems with annoyance,\nas it is possible that a greater annoyance is felt as a result of a confused brain attributing the sounds. This\nis in line with the theory of soundscape, where it is suggested that soundscape perception is of primary\nimportance for evaluating a scene, rather than the sounds within it.\nLastly, the differences observed highlight the possible interest in integrating perceptual tests and\npsychoacoustic parameters and annoyance modelling [20-24]. A key psychoacoustic result is that overall\nImpulsiveness (Hearing Model) was the strongest correlate of mean annoyance.\n\n5. Conclusion\nThis study aimed to explore the level of annoyance in short duration multi-source AVAS scenes using\na binaural auralization technique with single- and two-vehicle pass-by sounds. In N=10 participants,\nsimultaneous two-vehicle scenes were rated significantly more annoying than single-vehicle stimuli on\nthe raw 0–100 scale. The result supports a scene-based view of AVAS evaluation, in which the multisource context can change annoyance responses compared with isolated presentations. Furthermore, the\nincreased annoyance in multi-source scenes could not be explained by residual level differences.\nLimitations include the small number of participants, the limited set of stimuli, and the fixed speed.\nFuture work is needed to increase the number of the stimulus set, including more AVAS scenes, types of\nvehicles, and types of background sounds. It is also important to extend the scene manipulation space to\ninclude more than two vehicles, varying the lane distance, and including realistic intersection scenarios.\nFinally, it is important to explore the use of psychoacoustic and scene-based metrics as predictors of\nmulti-source AVAS annoyance, in order to allow the use of optimization models in relation to the design\nof AVAS scenes in realistic traffic scenarios.\n\nAcknowledgments\nThis work was supported by the Joint project 6G-life, under Grant 16KISK001K and as a part of\nGermany’s Excellence Strategy – EXC 2050/1 – Project ID 390696704 – Cluster of Excellence “Centre\nfor Tactile Internet with Human-in-the-Loop” (CeTI) of TU Dresden. This work was supported by the\nDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG, German Research Foundation) -444809588 as a part of the\npriority program AUDICTIVE - SPP2236. This conference participation was supported by the German\nAcademic Exchange Service (DAAD) under the Kongressreisenprogramm.\n\nREFERENCES\n1. World Health Organization. Environmental noise guidelines for the European Region, WHO\n\nRegional Office for Europe (2019).\n\n6│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\n2. R. Guski, D. Schreckenberg and R. Schuemer, “WHO Environmental Noise Guidelines for\n\nthe European Region: A systematic review on environmental noise and annoyance,”\nInternational Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, 14(12), 1539 (2017).\n3. R. Hanna, Incidence of Pedestrian and Bicyclist Crashes by Hybrid Electric Passenger\n\nVehicles (DOT HS 811 204), National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, Washington,\nDC (2009).\n4. J. Wu, R. Austin and C.-L. Chen, Incidence Rates of Pedestrian and Bicyclist Crashes by\n\nHybrid Electric Passenger Vehicles: An Update (DOT HS 811 526), National Highway\nTraffic Safety Administration, Washington, DC (2011).\n5. L. Garay-Vega, A. Hastings, J. K. Pollard, M. Zuschlag and M. D. Stearns, Quieter Cars and\n\nthe Safety of Blind Pedestrians: Phase I (DOT HS 811 304), National Highway Traffic Safety\nAdministration / Volpe Center, Washington, DC (2010).\n6. D. S. Kim, R. Wall Emerson, K. Naghshineh, J. Pliskow and K. Myers, “Impact of adding\n\nartificially generated alert sound to hybrid electric vehicles on their detectability by\npedestrians who are blind,” Journal of Rehabilitation Research and Development, 49(3),\n381–393 (2012). DOI: 10.1682/jrrd.2011.03.0041.\n7. E. Altinsoy, “The detectability of conventional, hybrid and electric vehicle sounds by\n\nsighted, visually impaired and blind pedestrians,” in Proceedings of INTER-NOISE 2013,\nInnsbruck, Austria (2013).\n8. J. Grosse, R. Weber and S. Van de Par, “Comparison of detection threshold measurements\n\nand modeling for approaching electric cars and conventional cars presented in traffic and\npink noise,” Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics, 19, 050192 (2013). DOI:\n10.1121/1.4806658.\n9. E. Parizet, W. Ellermeier and R. Robart, “Auditory warnings for electric vehicles:\n\nDetectability in normal-vision and visually-impaired listeners,” Applied Acoustics, 86, 50–\n58 (2014). DOI: 10.1016/j.apacoust.2014.05.006.\n10. P. Poveda-Martínez, R. Peral-Orts, N. Campillo-Davo, J. Nescolarde-Selva, M. Lloret-\n\nCliment and J. Ramis-Soriano, “Study of the effectiveness of electric vehicle warning sounds\ndepending on the urban environment,” Applied Acoustics (2017). DOI:\n10.1016/j.apacoust.2016.10.003.\n11. M.-C. Hsieh, H.-J. Chen, M.-L. Tong and C.-W. Yan, “Effect of environmental noise,\n\ndistance and warning sound on pedestrians’ auditory detectability of electric vehicles,”\nInternational Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, 18(17), 9290 (2021).\n12. M. J. Roan, L. Neurauter, M. Song and M. Miller, “Probability of detection of electric\n\nvehicles with and without added warning sounds,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of\nAmerica, 149(1), 599 (2021). DOI: 10.1121/10.0003386.\n13. L. Müller, J. Forssén and W. Kropp, “Auditory localization of multiple stationary electric\n\nvehicles,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, 157(3), 2029–2041 (2025).\nDOI: 10.1121/10.0036248.\n14. H. M. E. Miedema, “Relationship between exposure to multiple noise sources and noise\n\nannoyance,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, 116(2), 949–957 (2004).\nDOI: 10.1121/1.1766305.\n7│8\n\n\fICSV32, Annual Congress of International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), 5 - 10 July 2026\n\n15. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO/TS 15666:2021, Acoustics—\n\nAssessment of noise annoyance by means of social and socio-acoustic surveys, ISO (2021).\n16. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 532-1:2017, Acoustics—Methods\n\nfor calculating loudness—Part 1: Zwicker method, ISO (2017).\n17. International Organization for Standardization (ISO). ISO 532-2:2017, Acoustics—Methods\n\nfor calculating loudness—Part 2: Moore-Glasberg method, ISO (2017).\n18. Ecma International. ECMA-418-2: Psychoacoustic metrics for ITT equipment —Part 2\n\n(methods for describing human perception based on the Sottek Hearing Model), 4th edition,\nEcma International (2025).\n19. G. Q. Di, “Improvement of Zwicker’s psychoacoustic annoyance model aiming at tonal\n\nnoises,” Applied Acoustics (2016).\n20. H. Campello-Vicente, R. Peral-Orts, N. Campillo-Davo and E. Velasco-Sanchez, “The effect\n\nof electric vehicles on urban noise maps,” Applied Acoustics, 116, 59–64 (2017). DOI:\n10.1016/j.apacoust.2016.09.018